    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Vim has a built-in operator to ROT13 transform text, via `g?`. This is useless cruft in the same vein as `:smile`, which neovim removed. As such, I propose that the ROT13 operator should be removed/replaced. It looks like I'm not the first person to think of this, as it was brought up in #6263, but unfortunately was never seen through. The obstacle there seemed to be the desire to *replace* the existing operator as opposed to removing it. If that is still desired, I propose that `g?` be reassigned to comment/uncomment the selection. Commenting/uncommenting code is a very common operation across all programming languages, and neovim already has enough information to know how to comment/uncomment different filetypes via the `commentstring`. Furthermore, there are existing high-quality, zero-dependency implementations of this functionality that could be used as a reference for neovim's implementation such as [tpope/vim-commentary](https://github.com/tpope/vim-commentary), or even co-opted into neovim directly (like the `man.vim` and `matchit` plugins have been). **If this enhancement is given the go-ahead, I'd be happy to implement it myself.**\r\n",
