            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": ">Vim has a built-in operator to ROT13 transform text, via g?. This is useless cruft in the same vein as :smile, which neovim removed.\r\n\r\nNot really. `:smile` was just never ported to neovim while `g?` already exists.\r\n\r\n>As such, I propose that the ROT13 operator should be removed/replaced.\r\n\r\nRemoving something for the sake of removing it does not sound like a good idea to me. However, it does look like `g?`'s implementation is pretty complex: https://github.com/neovim/neovim/search?q=rot13 . So if it causes maintenance issues (I don't know if it does, the maintainers should probably weigh in), it would probably make sense to remove it. However, if it doesn't, it probably shouldn't be removed as its code seems to be tightly intertwined with other features and the removal risks both making porting patches from Vim harder and introducing new bugs.\r\n\r\n>I propose that g? be reassigned to comment/uncomment the selection.\r\n\r\nI think the discussion about adding comment/uncomment to neovim deserves its own github issue. It's a complicated matter and there are various approaches available here (regular textual changes that can fail, something more robust with tree-sitter...).",
